SC 4 creates a Task Force titled "ISO 10303 SMRL Architecture innovation"
with the following term of reference:

1. Taking into account the workshop report out and phasing plan proposal,
develop a detailed plan with recommendations for implementation;

2. Coordinate with other affected groups in SC4 on plan elements;

3. Provide periodic status reports to SC 4/PPC;

4. Deliver a final report to SC 4 on a schedule agreeable between the Task
Force and SC4

SC 4 requests its Secretariat to apply the 2-month duration to NPs for:

* 18828-3 Information Flows within Production Systems Engineering;
* 15926-6e2 Scope and Representation for Additional Reference Data -- OWL Extension;
* 15926-10 Conformance Testing;
* 15926: Initial Reference Data for the Maritime Industry;
* 15926 Integrated Lifecycle Asset Planning.

SC 4 resolves to change SC 4 Organization Handbook Clause 6.4 to read:

6.4 SC 4 Implementation Forum advisory group

6.4.1 Tasks
The SC 4 Implementation Forum advisory group performs the following tasks and activities:

* Gathering feed back from implementers;
* Gathering success stories;
* Promoting business benefits;
* Promoting awareness of capabilities;
* Facilitating implementations;
** Testing models and Testing procedures;
* Seeking resources for sustainment;
* Providing education and outreach.

It incorporates the activities of the former Committee for Education and Outreach, which has been disbanded.

6.4.2 Membership
The P-members, O-Members and A-liaisons of SC 4 nominate the members of the SC 4 Implementation Forum advisory group.

The SC 4 secretariat maintains a list of members of the SC 4 Implementation Forum (names and addresses, organization affiliation, fax, phone and e-mail).

SC 4 expresses its particular thanks to Mr. Fernando Santana, Director of Faculdade de Ciencias e Tecnologia da Universidade Nova de Lisboa, Mr. Adolfo Steiger-Garcao, Mr. Ricardo Jardim Gonçalves and Mrs. Cristina Gorba, and their on-location support staff;

Bruno Almeida, Marco Delgado, Maria Brazão, Sérgio Onofre, Maria Marques, Pedro Maló, Ruben Costa, Nelson Alves, Moisés Dutra, Miguel Beça, Fátima Brazão, Carlos Agostinho, Hugo Vieira, Gustavo Fernandes, João Pedro Mendonça, Licínia Santos, João Sarraipa

for superior administrative support and outstanding hospitality, both before and during and after the ISO/TC 184/SC 4 meeting.

SC 4 agrees that the title and scope of AP239 shall be changed to read as follows:

Title: Application Protocol: Product life cycle support

Scope: This part of ISO 10303 will provide extension to the capabilities
of AP203 and AP214 (and hence the PDM Schema/Modules) to address
the requirements for Configuration Change Management over the full product life.
This part of ISO 10303 will address the information requirements needed to
define and deliver life cycle support to complex assets. This includes
specification of:

* the identification and composition of a product design from a
support viewpoint (as an extension of the PDM Modules);
* the definition of documents and their applicability to products and
support activities (as an extension of the PDM Modules);
* the identification and composition of realized products;
* configuration change management activities, over the complete
life cycle;
* the properties, states and behaviour of products for life cycle
support;
* activities required to sustain product function;
* the resources needed to perform such activities;
* the planning and scheduling such activities;
* the capture of feedback on the performance of such activities,
including the resources used;
* the capture of feedback on the usage and condition of a realized
product;
* the definition of the support environment in terms of people,
organizations, skills, experience and facilities;
* the definition of classes of product, activities, states, people,
organizations and resources.

SC 4 therefore directs its Quality Committee to develop an initial set of guidelines for the
use of HTML. These guidelines should be available as a draft for comment by the San Francisco
meeting in June 2001, and should at least address the following topics:

* version(s) of HTML to be used;
* HTML tags to be used for the different elements of SC 4 standards;
* validation of HTML documents;
* naming conventions for files and directories;
* hyperlinks within documents and between documents.

SC 4 requests that its members, liaisons and other organizations provide additional resources to support this effort in the following areas:

11. finalizing requirements;
12. resolving the remaining technical and organizational issues;
13. reviewing and commenting on guideline documents;
14. using the modular approach and providing feedback to WG 10;
15. Addressing the use of ITAs, PASs and TSs within SC 4.

In order to provide a firm foundation for the next release of SC 4 standards tentatively scheduled for 2003, SC 4 requests:

* P-members to supply statements of user requirements for this timescale, taking into account the strategic plan for SC 4 and the requirements document WG 10 N 173, in writing to the Secretariat by 15 September 1998;
* Working groups and the Quality Committee, as well as the leaders of any PWI work, to supply statements of any input and key milestones for technology and development processes, in writing to the QC Change Management Team leader by 15 September 1998. The PPC and Change Management Team are requested to make a progress report for consideration by the SC 4 meeting in Beijing.

SC 4 approves extending the scope of the SEDS procedures to cover:

* SC 4 standing documents;
* SC 4 technical reports

SC 4 appoints Jack Skeels as Project Leader.

